04781nam a22006015i 9780520926882DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20022002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209268827 a10.1525/97805209268822doi  a(DE-B1597)519923  a(OCoLC)50667998  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aKF5605b.M47 2002eb 7aHIS0361402bisacsh04a333.74/09732211 aMerrill, Karen R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPublic Lands and Political Meaning :bRanchers, the Government, and the Property between Them /cKaren R. Merrill. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Policing And Policymaking On The Range -- t2. The Properties Of The Homebuilder -- t3. The Lessons Of The Market -- t4. The Sovereignty Of The State, Or The States? -- t5. The Taylor Grazing Act And The "Vast National Estate" -- t6. Property Rights And Political Meaning -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliographic Essay -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of the American West is a history of struggles over land, and none has inspired so much passion and misunderstanding as the conflict between ranchers and the federal government over public grazing lands. Drawing upon neglected sources from organized ranchers, this is the first book to provide a historically based explanation for why the relationship between ranchers and the federal government became so embattled long before modern environmentalists became involved in the issue. Reconstructing the increasingly contested interpretations of the meaning of public land administration, Public Lands and Political Meaning traces the history of the political dynamics between ranchers and federal land agencies, giving us a new look at the relations of power that made the modern West.Although a majority of organized ranchers supported government control of the range at the turn of the century, by midcentury these same organizations often used a virulently antifederal discourse that fueled many a political fight in Washington and that still runs deep in American politics today. In analyzing this shift, Merrill shows how profoundly people's ideas about property wove their way into the political language of the debates surrounding public range policy. As she unravels the meaning of this language, Merrill demonstrates that different ideas about property played a crucial role in perpetuating antagonism on both sides of the fence.In addition to illuminating the origins of the "sagebrush rebellions" in the American West, this book also persuasively argues that political historians must pay more attention to public land management issues as a way of understanding tensions in American state-building.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aGovernment ownershipxHistoryxUnited States. 0aGovernment ownershipzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPasture, Right ofxHistoryxUnited States. 0aPasture, Right ofzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPublic landsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aPublic landszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRanchersxLegal status, laws, etcxHistoryxUnited States. 0aRanchersxLegal status, laws, etczUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926882423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers